  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="29" relname="span">Michael Ruse, Profesor of philosophy and zoology at U. Guelph in Ontario,
has contributed a review of our friends Gross and Levitt&apos;s volume
in &quot;The Sciences,&quot;  Nov/Dec. 1994 34(6):39-44.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="background">  This is produced by
The New York Academy of Sciences.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="23" relname="span">

Struggle for the Soul of Science: Do Attacks from the Academic Left Pose
the Threat of Cultural War </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="3" relname="justify">(from the cover)</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="5" relname="nonvolitional-cause">

A gallimaufry of critics have been taunting science to defend its
objectivity.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="19" relname="span">  Now their quarry has begun to strike back... </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="19" relname="justify">(subtitle from
table of contents)</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="20" relname="span">

Articulate, well-placed scholars argue that science is biased to its
deepest roots.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="6" relname="elaboration">  The hatred of science is real and deep...</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="20" relname="justify"> (captioned
text)</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="12" relname="concession">

The review places most of the science-bashing blame on (we) pesky
feminists.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="26" relname="span">  Ruse does take issue with a number of points</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="antithesis"> (e.g.
Gross and Levitt reject metaphor,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="25" relname="span"> Ruse discusses how human
thought is &quot;deeply, universally, and necessarily metaphorical)</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="27" relname="span">
but doesn&apos;t pay attention to the problem of whether critical
science studies is uniformally &quot;lefty,&quot; and other similar generalizations
convenient to Gross and Levitt. </segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="28" relname="span"> That is, not all sci/tech studies
is critical,</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="16" relname="elaboration"> and what does &quot;left&quot; mean anymore anyway?</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="31" relname="background">

For your amusement.</segment>
